1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:04,000
There's a new kid on the protocol block.
No, not the 90s boy band.

2
00:00:04,300 --> 00:00:07,600
MCP-S
Verifiable runtime evidence for MCP calls.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:11,840
MCP gives agents a standard way to connect to tools,

4
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:15,920
source control, databases, internal docs, calendars,

5
00:00:15,920 --> 00:00:19,880
payment APIs, and the systems developers already use.

6
00:00:19,880 --> 00:00:21,840
That is why developers like it.

7
00:00:21,840 --> 00:00:25,160
Instead of one-off glue for every tool and every host,

8
00:00:25,160 --> 00:00:28,720
MCP gives us reusable integrations with a common shape.

9
00:00:28,720 --> 00:00:31,360
Host, client, server, tool.

10
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:33,920
But that call path is also a boundary.

11
00:00:33,920 --> 00:00:36,760
Once an agent asks a tool to do something sensitive,

12
00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:39,360
we need evidence about identity, integrity,

13
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:42,480
freshness, replay, and response binding.

14
00:00:42,480 --> 00:00:44,080
Take a payment request.

15
00:00:44,080 --> 00:00:48,800
The agent sends pay invoice 1042.

16
00:00:48,800 --> 00:00:51,680
If that call can be copied, replayed or changed,

17
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:54,160
one trusted action can become two bad ones.

18
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:01,960
MCP-S adds verifiable runtime evidence

19
00:01:01,960 --> 00:01:03,960
around those MCP calls.

20
00:01:03,960 --> 00:01:06,560
A request can carry a signature, a nonce,

21
00:01:06,560 --> 00:01:10,440
an expiry, authorization context, and a request hash.

22
00:01:10,440 --> 00:01:13,280
The response can be bound back with its own hash.

23
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:15,360
The point is not magic security.

24
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:17,160
The point is evidence that a verifier

25
00:01:17,160 --> 00:01:19,400
can check while the system is running.

26
00:01:19,400 --> 00:01:21,600
For enterprise deployments, signing keys

27
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:23,760
can stay in Google Cloud KMS.

28
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:26,240
MCP-S asks KMS to sign.

29
00:01:26,240 --> 00:01:28,440
The private key is not exported.

30
00:01:28,440 --> 00:01:32,000
MCP-S receives signatures, not raw key material.

31
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,440
The payoff is operational and testable.

32
00:01:34,440 --> 00:01:37,920
Valid requests are accepted, tampered requests are rejected,

33
00:01:37,920 --> 00:01:41,840
replays are rejected, and bad response bindings are rejected.

34
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:46,400
Try MCP-S at github.com/matssun/mcps.

